# Cursor Rules for Abcotronics ERP

## Primary Application Code Locations

The REAL application code that runs in production is located in:
- `src/` - React components, styles, utilities
- `api/` - Backend API endpoints
- Root level: `index.html`, `server.js`, `package.json`

## DO NOT Edit

- `frontend/` directory - This is a separate modernization project with placeholder code
- Files in `frontend/` are NOT used by the live application

## When Editing Components

Always edit files in `src/components/` not `frontend/src/components/`

Example:
- ✅ Correct: `src/components/projects/MonthlyDocumentCollectionTracker.jsx`
- ❌ Wrong: `frontend/src/components/projects/MonthlyDocumentCollectionTracker.jsx`

## Development Server

For local development of the real app, use:
- `npm run dev:backend` - Starts Express server serving the real app
- `npm run watch:jsx` - Watches and builds JSX files from `src/`

The `npm run dev` command starts both the real app AND the frontend modernization project. If you only need the real app, use `npm run dev:backend`.

## File Verification

Before editing, verify:
1. File path starts with `src/` or `api/` (not `frontend/`)
2. File is referenced in the build process or loaded by the server
3. Changes appear when testing with `npm run dev:backend`

## Before merging (build sanity)

For substantive UI work under `src/` that ships via the JSX pipeline:

- Run **`node build-jsx.js`** (or **`npm run build:jsx`**) before merge so `dist/` and `index.html` cache-bust stay consistent.
- If **`src/styles/main.css`** (or other Tailwind entry inputs) changed: **`npm run build:css`**.

Manufacturing/order API changes: still run **`npm run lint:audit`** (see **Manufacturing audit trail** later in this file).

## Where rules live

Treat **this file (repo-root `.cursorrules`)** as the canonical AI/project rule set. If you add **`.cursor/rules/`** entries later, avoid duplicating long policy in two places—keep one source of truth or sync both so guidance does not drift.

## Management meeting notes (General minutes inline comments)

- **Code:** `src/components/teams/ManagementMeetingNotes.jsx` only (not `frontend/`).
- **Data:** each week’s **`generalMinutes`** (HTML string) plus **`generalMinutesThreads`** (JSON: `id`, `start`, `end`, `quote`, `resolved`, `messages`).
- **DOM:** inline discussion anchors use **`span.gm-thread-anchor`** and **`data-gm-thread-id`**. The editor wrapper uses **`data-gm-editor-host`** (week id) for selection capture and click-to-thread in the sidebar.
- **API:** `api/meeting-notes.js` weekly update accepts `generalMinutes` / `generalMinutesThreads`; keep HTML and offset math aligned when changing this feature.

## Live updates and background refresh (list/detail views)

For list or detail views that poll or refetch (discussions, notifications, task comments, etc.):

- **Silent refresh**: When refreshing in the background (e.g. setInterval poll), do not set loading state or clear existing content. Pass a `silent: true` (or similar) option to the load function so the UI does not flash.
- **Append-only when possible**: For appendable lists (replies, comments, notifications), merge new items by ID instead of replacing the whole list: only append items that are not already in state so only new items appear and the rest of the screen does not re-render.
- **Reference equality**: When updating state after a silent fetch, avoid replacing the list/array if the data is unchanged (e.g. compare by id list) so React can avoid unnecessary re-renders.

Examples: `TeamDiscussions.jsx` (loadDetail with silent + reply merge), `NotificationCenter.jsx` (loadNotifications({ silent: true }) and only update list when ids changed).

**Meeting notes month poll:** when refetching `ManagementMeetingNotes` data in the background, follow the same ideas—avoid wiping focused editors or replacing lists wholesale; merge by id where possible.

## Manufacturing audit trail (mandatory for new mutations)

Any **new or changed** mutating route (POST, PATCH, DELETE) that affects Manufacturing or related order flows **must** write to `AuditLog` after a **successful** database change, using the existing helpers:

- **`api/manufacturing.js`**: call `auditManufacturing(action, resource, entityId, details)` immediately before each successful `return ok` / `return created` on mutation paths. Use `entity` semantics via the wrapper (`manufacturing` + `details.resource`).
- **`api/sales-orders.js`** and **`api/purchase-orders.js`**: call `logAuditFromRequest(prisma, req, { action, entity, entityId, details })` from `api/_lib/manufacturingAuditLog.js` with `entity` of `sales_orders` or `purchase_orders` respectively.

**Do not** rely on the browser `AuditLogger` alone for these APIs. **Do not** log successful GET/list/detail unless product explicitly requires read auditing. Failures in audit writes must stay non-fatal (use `void` on the promise where appropriate); never let audit logging break the main request.

When adding a new `resourceType` branch in `api/manufacturing.js` or new order endpoints, add audit coverage for **every** mutation exit that persists data.

Run **`npm run lint:audit`** before merging manufacturing/order API changes; ESLint enforces `auditManufacturing` / `logAuditFromRequest` before `ok`/`created` in `POST`/`PATCH`/`DELETE` branches (`eslint-rules/manufacturing-audit.mjs`).

## Manufacturing inventory: Option B (multi-warehouse truth)

- **Policy:** Every site that holds stock should have **movement rows attributed to that site** for ongoing operations (receipts, issues, transfers, adjustments). **`LEDGER_BASELINE_*` from `ledger-cutover-after-stocktake.js --mismatch-only`** is an exception: it anchors **combined** on-hand on **main office (01_LOC1)** only; use transfers / rebalance plan to align other bins in the ledger.
- **Authoritative mutations:** Persist **`StockMovement` + `LocationInventory`** (and master aggregates) in the **same transaction** via `applyStockCountAdjustmentTx` or manufacturing transfer / stock-movement APIs — not silent LI edits alone.
- **`StockMovement.fromLocation` / `toLocation`:** Prefer **location UUID** on all **new** writes (sales, PO goods receipt, manufacturing production paths, adjustments). Legacy rows may still hold codes; run `node scripts/backfill-stock-movement-location-ids.js --write` once when cleaning history.
- **Ledger-only cutover:** `scripts/ledger-cutover-after-stocktake.js` — default/cutoff modes compute implied opening **per `LocationInventory` row** from retained movements. **`--mismatch-only`** instead inserts **one** `LEDGER_BASELINE_*` row per mismatched SKU: **`fromLocation` = main office only** (`01_LOC1`, else `LOC001`), **`quantity` = total** on-hand (Σ locations). Use `plan:location-ledger-rebalance` + posted transfers if you need per-site movement truth to match bins.
- **Never hide drift** in the UI: disagreement between on-hand and movement math is a **data defect** — fix with posted movements or controlled scripts.
- **Combined alignment** (Σ LI vs combined movement net only): `npm run align:inventory-to-movements -- --dry-run` then `--write`. Does **not** fix per-site attribution. If an older adjustment-based align ran: `npm run undo:li-align-to-movements -- --write` first.
- **Verification:** `npm run verify:ledger` (company-wide) and `npm run verify:ledger:locations` (per warehouse row). `npm run verify:ledger:all` runs both.
- **Per-site rebalance plan (dry-run):** `npm run plan:location-ledger-rebalance` — suggests transfer legs to align movement story with current LI; review then post transfers in the app.
- **New inventory / ledger operational scripts:** add an **`npm run …` script in `package.json`** when operators are expected to run them, and a **one-line purpose comment** at the top of the script file (prefer **dry-run by default** for destructive or wide writes).

Legacy one-off imports (`scripts/import-stock-count-excel.js`, `STOCK_COUNT_IMPORT`) may use older movement location fields; normalize with `scripts/backfill-stock-movement-location-ids.js` when touching those rows.
